You could pad your strings to a defined length:

    let elements = [&quot;ITEM1&quot;, &quot;QTY&quot;, &quot;PRICE&quot;, &quot;TOTAL&quot;]
    
    // without padding
    var sentence = &quot;&quot;
    for e in elements {
        if !sentence.isEmpty {
            sentence += &quot; &quot;
        }
        sentence += e
    }
    
    print(sentence)
    // prints &quot;ITEM1 QTY PRICE TOTAL&quot;
    
    // with padding
    sentence = &quot;&quot;
    for e in elements {
        sentence += e.padding(toLength: 10, withPad: &quot; &quot;, startingAt: 0)
    }
    
    print(sentence)
    // prints &quot;ITEM1     QTY       PRICE     TOTAL     &quot;

Or in a shorter form:

    // without padding
    var sentence = elements.joined(separator: &quot; &quot;)
    print(sentence)
    
    // with padding
    sentence = elements.map({$0.padding(toLength: 10, withPad: &quot; &quot;, startingAt: 0)}).joined(separator: &quot; &quot;)
    print(sentence)

the section that you pass to your function is a placeholder for your array. it represents the element of your array. 

    section[0] decleration is wrong.

    let arr = [1,2];
    //arr[0] will give you 1;

    //but in your case your are trying to access arr[0][0]

    [1,2].filter( section =&gt; {
        //here first value for section will be 1 
        // do whatever you need in here by using the keyword section not section[0]
    });

Chalk this up to severe sleep deprivation . . . It turns out the `filter` was working as expected, but I think there is still (at least for me) a very important learning experience here and I hope my missteps will help others . . . 

What I ended up doing is tantamount to the following:

```
&gt;&gt; foo=[1,2,3]
//foo.length = 3
&gt;&gt; foo[&quot;blah&quot;] = 4
//foo:
//0: 1
//1: 2
//2: 3
//blah: 4
&gt;&gt; foo.length
// 3
// [Note: foo.length is still 3! I would have thought it now should be 4 after adding &quot;blah&quot;].
```
So in my original post, I thought I was replacing `this.datArr[2]` with the result of the filter, but in reality, I was effectively replacing `this.datArr[&quot;blah&quot;]` with the result of the filter. As a result `this.datArr[2]` remained unchanged (which caused me to mistakenly believe the filter wasn&#39;t working) AND `this.datArr.length` remained unchanged, so at first I had no idea that I was assigning the `filter` results to the wrong (new) entry in `this.datArr`.

